{"id":"1210.2321","submitter":"Ya Zhou","authors":"Ya Zhou, Alejandro Strachan","title":"Phonon thermal transport outside of local equilibrium in nanowires via\n  molecular dynamics","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1063/1.4793530","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall cond-mat.mtrl-sci physics.comp-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study thermal transport through Pt nanowires that bridge planar contacts\nas a function of wire length and vibrational frequency of the contacts. When\nphonons in the contacts have lower average frequencies than those in the wires\nthermal transport occurs under conditions away from local equilibrium with\nlow-frequency phonons experiencing a higher thermal gradient than\nhigh-frequency ones. This results in a size-dependent increase in the effective\nthermal conductivity of the wire with decreasing vibrational frequencies of the\ncontacts. The interfacial resistivity when heat flows from the wire to the\ncontact is also size-dependent and has the same physical origin in the lack of\nfull equilibration in short nanowires. We develop a model based on a 1D atomic\nchain that captures the salient physics of the MD results.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 8 Oct 2012 15:56:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-11"}
{"id":"1210.2322","submitter":"Takashi Kimura","authors":"Takashi Kimura","title":"Strong-coupling expansion for the spin-1 Bose-Hubbard model","comments":"22 pages, 11 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 87, 043624 (2013). Phys. Rev. A 87, 043624 (2013).\n  Phys. Rev. A 87, 043624 (2013)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.87.043624","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.quant-gas","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this study, we perform a strong-coupling expansion up to third order of\nthe hopping parameter $t$ for the spin-1 Bose--Hubbard model with\nantiferromagnetic interaction. As expected from previous studies, the Mott\ninsulator phase is considerably more stable against the superfluid phase when\nfilling with an even number of bosons than when filling with an odd number of\nbosons. The phase-boundary curves are consistent with the perturbative\nmean-field theory in the limit of infinite dimensions. The critical value of\nthe hopping parameter $t_{\\rm C}$ at the peak of the Mott lobe depends on the\nantiferromagnetic interaction. This result indicates the reliability of the\nstrong coupling expansion when $U_2$ possesses large (intermediate) values for\nMott lobe with an even (odd) number of bosons. Moreover, in order to improve\nour results, we apply a few extrapolation methods up to infinite order in $t$.\nThe fitting results of the phase-boundary curves agree better with those of the\nperturbative mean-field approximation. In addition, the linear fit error of\n$t_{\\rm C}$ is very small for the strong antiferromagnetic interaction.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 8 Oct 2012 15:57:41 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 22 Oct 2012 08:29:09 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 27 Mar 2013 14:56:54 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 9 Apr 2013 06:50:55 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Tue, 17 Dec 2013 04:27:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-11"}
{"id":"1210.2323","submitter":"Erick Nagel","authors":"Erick Nagel, Paola D'Alessio, Nuria Calvet, Catherine Espaillat and\n  Miguel Angel Trinidad","title":"The effect of sublimation temperature dependencies on disk walls around\n  T Tauri stars","comments":"17 pages, 6 figures, accepted for publication in Revista Mexicana de\n  Astronomia y Astrofisica","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.SR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The dust cannot survive closer to the star from the point where a grain\nreaches a temperature equal to the sublimation temperature. The boundary\nbetween a dust-free and a dusty region defines the sublimation wall. In the\nliterature two models for the structure of the wall are used: a wall with a\nfixed sublimation temperature and a wall with a density-dependent sublimation\ntemperature. In the former, the wall is vertical and in the latter, the wall is\ncurved. We find important differences between these models SEDs in the\nwavelength range from 3 to 8\\mu m, being the emission of the former larger than\nthat of the latter model. We quantify the differences in IRAC colors when these\nmodels are used to explain the observations. In the IRAC color-color diagram\n([3.6]-[4.5] vs. [5.8]-[8.0]), the models are located in specific regions,\neither depending on the inclination, the mass accretion rate, or which model is\nused.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 8 Oct 2012 15:58:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-10-09"}
